        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Baltic offensive against Russia </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: The Baltic countries are forming a coalition with Central European countries to tackle Russian dominance in the Baltic Sea.</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The what:</strong> The Baltic Sea region has been a hotspot of geopolitical tension since Russia’s war in Ukraine. Russia exploits this region to bypass sanctions and destabilize Europe through shadow fleet operations, cyberterrorism, and espionage. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          To tackle the dominance, Central European countries and the Baltic states are <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-jul-25-analysis-h1-7-cooperating-in-military-and-aid-funding" target="_blank">cooperating in military and aid funding</a>. It includes sending aid to Ukraine, the 2024 Latvian drone coalition (funding for drone production), and electric grid synchronization for better energy management. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The reason:</strong> The Baltic states remain a barrier between Russia and Europe, and the Baltic Sea also serves as a critical maritime hub for trade and military logistics. They are also among the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-top-10-in-nato-spending" target="_blank">Top 10 in NATO spending</a>, with over 2% of their GDP going to defense. They also promote EU enlargement, democratic values, and transatlantic cooperation, making them crucial for agencies like NATO to deter Russian threats. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The bigger picture:</strong> Poland has proposed strengthening control of the Baltic Sea and supported the NATO “Baltic Sentry” mission, along with its latest security strategy, to protect critical undersea infrastructure. Meanwhile, with the accession of Finland and Sweden to NATO, there has been a noticeable increase in air force monitoring, logistical support for the Baltic fleet (to monitor Russian shadow fleets), and they are working to secure the North Atlantic.  
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
