            ">What is Puerto Rico’s status?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/puerto-rico-2020-statehood-vote-results.jpg" alt="In the 2020 vote, almost 53% of voters supported becoming the 51st state of the American union. But nearly half of the electorate rejected this option" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>In the 2020 vote, almost 53% of voters supported becoming the 51st state of the American union. But nearly half of the electorate rejected this option. Credits: AP Photo</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The status:</strong> Puerto Rico is <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-jul-25-worldwide-h2-14-an-unincorporated-territory" target="_blank">an unincorporated territory</a> of the United States. The US government controls it, but it lacks full state rights. It has its local government and constitution, but it must still adhere to US federal laws. Puerto Ricans are US citizens, but they have no voting representation in Congress. They can vote in US presidential elections if they live in one of the 50 states. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The background:</strong> Puerto Rico became a US territory in 1898 after the Spanish-American War. It gained more autonomy with the 1952 constitution, which made it a US commonwealth. While the island’s inhabitants were granted US citizenship in 1917, there have been ongoing debates about what type of status the island should have throughout the 20th and 21st centuries. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
         <strong>The challenges:</strong> Even if the Puerto Ricans vote in a referendum, the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-jul-25-worldwide-h2-15-discretionary-powers" target="_blank">discretionary powers</a> lie with the US Congress. The US also questions the smooth transfer of citizenship, taxation, laws, and the economic liabilities it has to incur when Puerto Rico gains statehood. There is also fear among the politicians as the Puerto Ricans can lean towards a particular party, which could tilt the results. 
          </p>
